Package tage.rml

Interface Vector4

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Comparable<Vector4>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    Vector4f
    public interface Vector4
    This interface defines the operations for a 4-component vector.

    Implementations are meant to use a column-major layout. This is the standard convention followed by mathematical texts and OpenGL/GLSL.

    This interface implies this convention by the lack of a mult method expecting a matrix, where the vector being multiplied is on the left side of the matrix. In other words, it's not possible to take a matrix M and a vector v and multiply them as v' = vM to produce a new row vector v' as the output.

    For those with a Microsoft Direct3D background, note that they follow a convention opposite to the standard described above.

    Author:
    Raymond L. Rivera
    See Also:
    Matrix4

      • lengthSquared

        float lengthSquared()
        Returns the measured length of this instance without taking the square root.

        This method is provided for performance reasons. It avoids expensive square root operations for simple comparisons (e.g. sorting).

        Returns:
        The squared length of this instance.
        See Also:
        length()

      • isZeroLength

        boolean isZeroLength()
        Determines whether this instance has a length of zero or not.

        Zero-length instances should avoid calling normalize(). Doing so will result in an attempt to divide by zero.

        Returns:
        True if this instance is zero-length. False otherwise.
        See Also:
        length(), lengthSquared()

      • dot

        float dot​(T o)
        Returns the scalar dot-product.

        The dot-product, also known as the inner product, will be a scalar value in the [-1, 1] range because it's the cosine of the angle between them, not the angle itself. In other words, for the scalar value to actually represent an angle, in radians, you must calculate the inverse cosine of it.

        Parameters:
        o - The instance used to calculate the dot-product.
        Returns:
        The scalar value of the dot-product.
